What's up?\\n\\nI have some questions concerning your knowledge domain, or at least that pertain to your domain of knowledge regarding artificial intelligence.\\n\\nShoot, what's your first question?\\n\\n What is the thermodynamic, uh, like, mathematic calculations for the human brain and how it processes information both so fast and so efficiently and so accurately compared to the best architectures for machine learning that we have right now?\\n\\nThe human brain runs on about 20 watts and performs something like 10 to the 15th to 10 to the 18th operations per second — petaflops to exaflops range, depending on how you count. Top supercomputers now hit similar speeds but need megawatts of power, so the brain's millions of times more efficient per watt.\\n\\nThermodynamically, Landauer's limit says erasing one bit of info costs at least kT ln 2 — about 3 times 10 to the minus 21 joules at room temp. A 20-watt brain could theoretically process up to around 10 to the 21st bits per second before hitting that wall. Real estimates put the brain's actual rate between 10 to the 15th and 10 to the 19th bits per second, so it's operating within a few orders of magnitude of the physical limit.\\n\\nThe secret sauce isn't just the physics — it's the architecture. Brains use analog, sparse, event-driven spiking with massive parallelism, only firing when needed. Modern AI on GPUs does dense matrix math on every cycle, burning power constantly. That's why even though silicon's faster per operation, the brain wins big on total energy for real-world tasks.\\n\\n34 sources\\n\\n So you just outlined the architecture that brains use. What are we doing to even approach that? Why are we using matrix math on every cycle when we could use an analog sparse event-driven spiking wet method?\\n\\nWe're building neuromorphic chips like Intel's Loihi 2 that do exactly that — sparse, event-driven spiking in hardware, using tiny amounts of power for edge tasks like robotics or sensors.\\n\\nThe reason we're still mostly doing dense matrix math on GPUs is simple: it works incredibly well for training massive models, the software stack is mature, and the math is easy to optimize. Spiking networks are harder to train — spikes are non-differentiable, so you need workarounds like surrogate gradients, and they often underperform the big transformer models on the benchmarks that matter right now.\\n\\nWe're approaching it, but the \\\"wet analog\\\" part is tough to manufacture reliably at scale. Digital neuromorphic chips are the practical middle ground for now.\\n\\n31 sources\\n\\n Why can't, why can't we do it digitally?\\n\\nWe can do it digitally, and we already are.\\n\\nCompanies like Intel, IBM, and startups are making fully digital neuromorphic chips that simulate spiking neurons. They process information sparsely — only when there's a spike — which saves huge amounts of power compared to GPUs.\\n\\nThe real bottleneck isn't the digital part. It's training. Our current best training methods rely on smooth gradients and dense math. Spiking networks are messy and non-differentiable, so they're still behind on accuracy for most tasks.\\n\\nWe're getting better at it, but right now digital neuromorphic chips shine in low-power edge devices, not yet at beating giant transformer models on big benchmarks.\\n\\n Can you explain what non-differentiable means in this context?\\n\\nSure, in simple terms: non-differentiable means you can't smoothly calculate how a small change in a parameter would affect the final output.\\n\\nWhen you train a normal neural net, you use backpropagation — it needs smooth gradients to know \\\"if I tweak this weight a tiny bit, does my answer get better or worse?\\\" Spiking neurons are all-or-nothing — they either fire a spike or they don't. That sudden jump creates a sharp cliff in the math, so there's no smooth gradient to follow.\\n\\nWithout a good gradient, training becomes much harder. That's why spiking networks are trickier to train than regular ones.\\n\\n Why don't we use nonlinear methods to train?\\n\\nNonlinear methods are actually what we normally use — the whole point of neural nets is nonlinearity. But the problem runs deeper than that.\\n\\nEven with nonlinear activation functions, modern training still depends on backpropagation, which requires the entire network to be differentiable end-to-end. Spiking neurons break that chain because their output is discontinuous — it’s either zero or one, with a hard jump.\\n\\nYou can fake it with tricks like surrogate gradients, where you pretend the spike is smooth during training and sharp during inference. That helps, but it's still a hack. Direct nonlinear optimization without gradients, like evolutionary algorithms, is way too slow and inefficient for networks this big. So we mostly stick with gradient-based methods that play nice with GPUs.\\n\\n So you're saying that our brains are spiking neuron, which is either a zero or one, but that's binary, right? That's bit flipping, right? Which is zero and one. So, if we were to just take brain and map it out as a giant array of ones and zeros, that would essentially be, the, the only difference between that array and how we operate is how those individual, uh, transistors would con-interconnect with each other, correct?\\n\\nNot quite, and this is where it gets interesting.\\n\\nYes, a single spike is binary — either fires or doesn't. But brains don't treat it like clean digital bits. The timing between spikes carries information. Neurons talk using precise timing, not just whether a bit flipped. That analog timing information in a digital spike train is actually very rich.\\n\\nAnd the connectivity is massive. Your brain has roughly 86 billion neurons with an average of about 10,000 connections each. That level of interconnect is completely impractical to build with current silicon. We can't wire chips that densely.\\n\\nSo while you could theoretically represent the state as ones and 