 now, then why can't we do it with hardware?\\n\\nIt's not just about making transistors smaller. The real killer is interconnect density.\\n\\nYour brain has roughly 86 billion neurons but around 100 to 200 trillion synapses — each neuron connects to thousands of others on average in a highly irregular 3D way. Even the world's biggest neuromorphic system right now, Intel's Hala Point, only reaches about 1.15 billion neurons and 128 billion synapses. That's roughly 1% of the brain's neuron count and a fraction of one percent of its connections.\\n\\nPacking that many flexible, reconfigurable connections into silicon while keeping power and heat under control is insanely hard. Our chips are still mostly 2D with limited wiring layers. The brain's 3D wet architecture is just on another level. We're making progress, but we're not close yet.\\n\\n31 sources\\n\\n Why would the heat be an issue if we don't have an issue with that many connections in our brain? Why would the heat be an issue if, if, let's say, let's say that we could theoretically build a 3D chip that was fully interconnected with the same degree as our brain, why would heat be the same, why would heat be an issue for this chip when it's not that much of an issue for us?\\n\\nTwo big reasons.\\n\\nFirst, power density. Even though a brain uses about 20 watts total, it's spread over a much larger volume — your brain is softball-sized. A chip crams way more activity into a tiny area, so heat builds up in hotspots fast.\\n\\nSecond, cooling. Your brain has blood constantly flowing through it, carrying heat away like a built-in liquid cooling system. A 3D silicon chip has no equivalent — heat gets trapped inside layers with poor thermal paths, and silicon isn't great at moving heat laterally once you make the layers super thin.\\n\\nEven if we could match the brain's wiring density, dissipating the heat efficiently in solid silicon is a totally different engineering problem than what biology solved with wet, flowing coolant.\\n\\n39 sources\\n\\n But that's a contradiction right there. Because you're talking about the brain's wiring density, even though the brain is much bigger and less dense than a chip. So what if we made chips about as dense as the brain, then made it as big as a brain?\\n\\nIt's not a contradiction — it's about how the energy is used and removed.\\n\\nEven if you made a neuromorphic chip the physical size of a brain with the same neuron density, silicon transistors switch billions of times per second, while brain neurons fire maybe 10 times per second on average. That speed difference means way more switching events per second, generating far more heat.\\n\\nPlus, the brain has blood flow actively pulling heat away molecule-by-molecule. A big 3D silicon structure would still rely on passive conduction and maybe fans, which gets inefficient deep inside the volume. So you'd need either slower operation or serious cooling tech to match the brain's 20 watts without cooking itself.\\n\\n35 sources\\n\\n But, but, but, why would we need to make the silicon chips switch faster if the neurons in our brain don't switch that fast?\\n\\nBecause silicon chips are fundamentally bad at being slow.\\n\\nTo do useful work, a silicon transistor needs to switch fast enough to justify its existence — otherwise it's wasting space. If you slow a chip down to match brain neuron speeds (say 10-100 Hz), you get almost nothing done. You could only do a tiny fraction of what the brain does.\\n\\nThe brain solves this beautifully with massive parallelism — it has orders of magnitude more neurons working in parallel than anything we can build. So each neuron can be slow, but there are so many of them working simultaneously that the system is still fast overall.\\n\\nSilicon doesn't get that same advantage because we can't build systems with hundreds of trillions of slow parallel elements. So we make each transistor much faster to compensate.\\n\\n Yes! Okay, okay, but pause, pa