 be, um, uh, mathematic, like, or a, a evolutionary perfect, um, sparse neural network? Would it be efficient? Would it work?\\n\\nYes, it would be efficient.\\n\\nOnce the evolutionary algorithm finishes and you have the final sparse network, running it — doing inference — would be very efficient. You only compute the connections that actually exist, so you're doing much less math than a dense network.\\n\\nThe final network itself would absolutely work. Many papers have shown that properly evolved sparse networks can match or come very close to the accuracy of dense networks while using a fraction of the computation and memory.\\n\\nThe only real downside is the upfront cost to discover that good sparse structure. But once you have it, yes — the final network is both mathematically efficient and effective.\\n\\n Okay, okay, okay, okay. Before we go on to the next topic, I have question, and it is, how does, what, what is the transformer model? What does the large language model have to do with neural networks? How, how is it different? What does it augment in terms of the connectionist methodology?\\n\\nTransformers are a specific type of neural network architecture.\\n\\nHere's the simple breakdown:\\n\\nA normal neural network passes information in one direction, layer by layer.\\nTransformers are different because they use something called self-attention. This lets every word in a sentence look at every other word at the same time, no matter how far apart they are. It figures out which words are important to each other.\\n\\nSo when you use ChatGPT or Grok, the large language model is built on the transformer architecture. It's still a neural network, but instead of using regular layers, it uses stacks of these attention layers.\\n\\nThe big thing it augments is context understanding — it can connect ideas across very long pieces of text much better than older neural network designs could. That's why LLMs suddenly got so good at language.\\n\\n Okay, and what a