use they can take full advantage of GPUs, which are designed for massive parallel computation. Basic neural networks couldn't do that nearly as well.\\n\\n Why did neural networks have to process sequentially? They're a, really, they're connectionists. They, shouldn't they be as parallel as however you make them?\\n\\nGood question.\\n\\nThe issue wasn't with neural networks in general — it was with Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs), which were the dominant architecture before transformers.\\n\\nHere's why they had to be sequential:\\n\\nIn an RNN, each word's output becomes the input for the next word. So word 5 literally depends on the calculation of word 4, which depends on word 3, and so on.\\nYou literally cannot calculate word 5 until you've finished calculating all the previous words. This forces sequential processing.\\n\\nRegular feedforward neural networks are parallel, but they had their own problem — they had no memory of previous words at all.\\n\\nTransformers solved both problems at once: they’re fully parallel and they have excellent memory of everything that came before. That combination is what made them so powerful.\\n\\n Why do regular feed-forward neural networks not have any memory of the previous words at all?\\n\\nSimple and direct answer:\\n\\nBecause a regular feed-forward neural network has no loops and no memory.\\n\\nEach input goes through the network once, produces an output, and that's it. The network has no idea what it processed 5 words ago — it has no memory at all.\\n\\nWhen you feed it a sentence like \\\"The cat sat on the...\\\", it only sees one word at a time. By the time it gets to the word \\\"the\\\", it has completely forgotten what \\\"cat\\\" or \\\"sat\\\" was. There's no mechanism to carry information from one word to the next.\\n\\nThat's why basic feed-forward networks were terrible at language tasks — they had no way to understand context or sequence.\\n\\n Why did you feed it, why would we feed a, a sentence one word at a time? Why not feed it the entire sentence at once?\\n\\nBecause the architecture didn't allow it.\\n\\nIn a basic feed-forward neural network, the input layer has a fixed size. If you design the network to accept 10 words, it can only take exactly 10 words — no more, no less.\\n\\nIf your sentence has 15 words, you can't feed the whole thing in at once. You'd have to either:\\n\\nCut the sentence down, or\\nFeed it one word (or a few words) at a time\\n\\nThe network had no natural way to handle variable-length sequences or to look at all words simultaneously. That was its fundamental limitation.\\n\\nTransformers solved this by using attention, which can naturally handle any length of text and process everything at once.\\n\\n Why didn't we just make the input layer for a neural network as large as possible?\\n\\nTwo practical reasons:\\n\\nMemory waste\\nIf you make the input layer big enough to handle a 10,000-word document, then for a normal 20-word sentence, 99% of your input neurons would be empty (padded with zeros). This wastes massive amounts of memory and computation.\\nFixed size limitation\\nEven if you make it huge, it’s still fixed. If a text is longer than your maximum size, you still can’t process it. So you’re either extremely wasteful on short text or you fail completely on long text.\\n\\nThis is why a fixed-size input layer was never a good solution. It’s extremely inefficient and inflexible. Transformers don’t have this problem because they can handle any length naturally.\\n\\n And how can transformers handle any length naturally again?\\n\\nBecause of how Self-Attention works.\\n\\nIn a transformer, every word can directly talk to every other word — no matter if the sentence is 10 words long or 500 words long.\\n\\nThe key point is this:\\nTransformers don’t have a fixed-size input layer like old neural networks. The attention mechanism can dynamically calculate relationships between however many words are actually in the input.\\n\\nI