blem. It's a **meta-cognition / epistemic humility** problem in agents.\n\n### How I would describe the fundamental problem:\n\n**\"The Infinite Implicit Context Problem\"**\n\nOr more formally:\n\n> In any sufficiently real task, there exists an **unknowably large set of implicit constraints, preferences, identity signals, aesthetic standards, past decisions, emotional valences, brand considerations, and environmental nuances** that are material to success. The human cannot enumerate them all. The agent has no privileged access to them. Yet the agent is expected to act as if it understands the full context.\n\nThis creates a permanent gap between:\n- What the user *actually* wants (a rich, entangled outcome)\n- What the user *can explicitly describe* (a thin slice)\n- What the agent *can discover without guidance* (another thin slice)\n\nIt's the problem of **unknown unknowns** applied to human intent.\n\n### Why it's so hard to solve\n\nYou cannot \"list all of them\" because:\n- Many are tacit (you only notice them when violated)\n- Many are contextual and change over time\n- Many live in the user's emotional/systemic memory, not in any document\n- The very act of listing them changes the task\n\n### How I currently try to deal with it (honestly)\n\nMy current strategies are still crude:\n\n1. **Memory + User Profile** — I have persistent facts about you (Reagent Systems, high-energy founder style, n8n setup, security preferences, etc.).\n2. **Skill system** — I load relevant procedural memory before acting.\n3. **Session search** — I look through past conversations for patterns.\n4. **Preemptive clarification** on things I *know* I don't know.\n5. **Verification layers** after generation (this is what your `tri_verify` was trying to do).\n\nBut these are all **reactive** or **partially sighted**. They don't solve the fundamental issue that the space of relevant implicit context is effectively infinite and mostly invisible.\n\n---\n\nThis is one of the deepest op